## 1. Introduction

### 1.1 Scope

This task covers the bundling of all SDLC pipeline resources into the VS Code extension package (kiro-sdlc-agents). The extension must include agent definitions, steering rules, hooks, and document templates that are copied from the source project (MCPOrchestration) into the extension’s resources/ directory during the build process, and then injected into target workspaces when users run the extension commands.

The bundled resources form the core value of the extension — they provide a complete multi-agent SDLC pipeline (BA, SA, QA, DEV, DevOps, UI, Security, SM, TA) that can be injected into any Kiro IDE workspace.

### 1.2 Out of Scope

* Extension TypeScript source code logic (covered by other KSA tickets)
* Code Intelligence indexer scripts (separate component)
* Extension marketplace publishing workflow
* Runtime behavior of agents after injection (agent execution is Kiro IDE responsibility)

### 1.3 Preliminary Requirements

* Source project (MCPOrchestration) must have all agent, steering, hook, and template files finalized
* Build scripts (copy-resources.js, gen-checksums.js) must be functional
* Extension packaging tool (vsce) must be available

## 2. Business Requirements

### 2.1 High Level Process Map

The bundled resources flow follows this lifecycle:

1. **Source** — Agent/steering/hook/template files are authored in the MCPOrchestration project
2. **Sync** — sync-from-source.ps1 copies changed files to FEC\_CR\_Builder workspace
3. **Bundle** — copy-resources.js copies files from workspace root into kiro-sdlc-agents/resources/
4. **Checksum** — gen-checksums.js generates .sdlc-checksums.json manifest with SHA-256 hashes
5. **Package** — vsce package bundles everything into a .vsix file
6. **Inject** — Extension commands copy resources from resources/ into target workspace

### 2.2 List of User Stories

|  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| # | Story / Use Case | Priority | Source Ticket |
| 1 | As a developer, I want all 9 SDLC agents bundled in the extension so that I can inject a complete multi-agent pipeline into my workspace | MUST HAVE | KSA-6 |
| 2 | As a developer, I want all 9 steering rules bundled so that injected agents follow consistent coding standards and workflows | MUST HAVE | KSA-6 |
| 3 | As a developer, I want all 8 hooks bundled so that code intelligence indexing and draw.io validation happen automatically | MUST HAVE | KSA-6 |
| 4 | As a developer, I want all document templates bundled so that agents can generate standardized SDLC documents | MUST HAVE | KSA-6 |
| 5 | As a developer, I want bundled resources to match the source project exactly so that I get the latest agent capabilities | MUST HAVE | KSA-6 |
| 6 | As a developer, I want a checksum manifest so that the extension can detect if I’ve customized any files | SHOULD HAVE | KSA-6 |

### 2.3 Details of User Stories

#### Business Flow

**Step 1:** Developer installs the kiro-sdlc-agents extension in VS Code/Kiro IDE

**Step 2:** Developer opens a workspace and runs “Kiro SDLC: Inject All Agents” command

**Step 3:** Extension reads bundled resources from its resources/ directory

**Step 4:** Extension copies agents to .kiro/agents/, steering to .kiro/steering/, hooks to .kiro/hooks/, templates to documents/templates/

**Step 5:** Extension generates .kiro/.sdlc-version file tracking the injected version

**Step 6:** Developer can now use all SDLC agents in their workspace

**Note:** The “Update” command detects user modifications via checksum comparison and offers skip/backup/overwrite options.

#### STORY 1: 9 Agents Bundled and Match Source

As a developer, I want all 9 SDLC agents bundled in the extension so that I can inject a complete multi-agent pipeline into my workspace.

**Requirement Details:**

1. The extension MUST bundle exactly 9 agent definitions, each consisting of a .json config file and a .md description file
2. Each agent MUST also have a detailed prompt file in agents/prompts/{agent-name}.md
3. All agent files MUST match the source project (MCPOrchestration/.kiro/agents/) byte-for-byte after sync

**Agent Inventory:**

|  |  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| # | Agent ID | JSON Config | Description | Prompt |
| 1 | ba-agent | ba-agent.json | ba-agent.md | prompts/ba-agent.md |
| 2 | dev-agent | dev-agent.json | dev-agent.md | prompts/dev-agent.md |
| 3 | devops-agent | devops-agent.json | devops-agent.md | prompts/devops-agent.md |
| 4 | qa-agent | qa-agent.json | qa-agent.md | prompts/qa-agent.md |
| 5 | sa-agent | sa-agent.json | sa-agent.md | prompts/sa-agent.md |
| 6 | security-agent | security-agent.json | security-agent.md | prompts/security-agent.md |
| 7 | sm-agent | sm-agent.json | sm-agent.md | prompts/sm-agent.md |
| 8 | ta-agent | ta-agent.json | ta-agent.md | prompts/ta-agent.md |
| 9 | ui-agent | ui-agent.json | ui-agent.md | prompts/ui-agent.md |

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. All 9 agents present in resources/.kiro/agents/ directory
2. Each agent has both .json and .md files
3. All 9 prompt files present in resources/.kiro/agents/prompts/
4. SHA-256 checksums in .sdlc-checksums.json match actual file hashes
5. Running copy-resources.js from source produces identical files

#### STORY 2: 9 Steering Files Bundled

As a developer, I want all 9 steering rules bundled so that injected agents follow consistent coding standards and workflows.

**Requirement Details:**

1. The extension MUST bundle exactly 9 steering rule files in .kiro/steering/
2. Steering files provide workspace-level rules that guide all agent behavior
3. Files MUST match source project

**Steering File Inventory:**

|  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- |
| # | File | Purpose |
| 1 | agent-self-learning.md | Agent learning and adaptation rules |
| 2 | backend-structure.md | Backend project structure conventions |
| 3 | code-intelligence.md | Code intelligence indexing rules |
| 4 | code-standards.md | General code standards (all languages) |
| 5 | drawio.md | Draw.io diagram creation rules |
| 6 | file-writing.md | File writing conventions |
| 7 | frontend-structure.md | Frontend project structure conventions |
| 8 | jira-workflow.md | Jira workflow integration rules |
| 9 | kotlin-code-standards.md | Kotlin-specific code standards |

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. All 9 steering files present in resources/.kiro/steering/
2. Each file has meaningful content (not empty/placeholder)
3. SHA-256 checksums match in manifest

#### STORY 3: 8 Hooks Bundled

As a developer, I want all 8 hooks bundled so that code intelligence indexing and draw.io validation happen automatically.

**Requirement Details:**

1. The extension MUST bundle exactly 8 hook files in .kiro/hooks/
2. Hooks provide automated triggers for file events (create, edit, delete)
3. Hook types: Code Intelligence indexing (4 hooks) + Draw.io validation (3 hooks) + File watcher (1 hook)

**Hook Inventory:**

|  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| # | File | Type | Trigger |
| 1 | code-index-create.json | Code Intelligence | File created |
| 2 | code-index-delete.json | Code Intelligence | File deleted |
| 3 | code-index-edit.json | Code Intelligence | File edited |
| 4 | code-index-full.json | Code Intelligence | Full re-index |
| 5 | file-watcher.sh | File Watcher | File system events |
| 6 | validate-drawio-edit.kiro.hook | Draw.io Validation | .drawio file edited |
| 7 | validate-drawio-xml.kiro.hook | Draw.io Validation | .drawio XML validation |
| 8 | validate-drawio.sh | Draw.io Validation | Shell-based validation |

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. All 8 hook files present in resources/.kiro/hooks/
2. JSON hooks have valid JSON structure
3. Shell scripts have proper shebang and are executable
4. .kiro.hook files follow Kiro hook format
5. SHA-256 checksums match in manifest

#### STORY 4: Document Templates Bundled

As a developer, I want all document templates bundled so that agents can generate standardized SDLC documents.

**Requirement Details:**

1. The extension MUST bundle document templates in documents/templates/
2. Templates cover the full SDLC lifecycle: requirements, specification, design, testing, deployment
3. Current source has 12 templates; acceptance criteria specifies 10 (minimum required for core SDLC pipeline)

**Template Inventory:**

|  |  |  |  |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| # | File | SDLC Phase | Required |
| 1 | BRD-TEMPLATE.md | Requirements | Yes |
| 2 | FSD-TEMPLATE.md | Specification | Yes |
| 3 | TDD-TEMPLATE.md | Design | Yes |
| 4 | STP-TEMPLATE.md | Test Planning | Yes |
| 5 | STC-TEMPLATE.md | Test Cases | Yes |
| 6 | DPG-TEMPLATE.md | Deployment | Yes |
| 7 | RLN-TEMPLATE.md | Release Notes | Yes |
| 8 | UG-TEMPLATE.md | User Guide | Yes |
| 9 | TEST-REPORT-TEMPLATE.md | Test Reporting | Yes |
| 10 | SECURITY-REPORT-TEMPLATE.md | Security | Yes |
| 11 | DESIGN-SYSTEM.md | UI Design | Optional |
| 12 | UI-SPEC-TEMPLATE.md | UI Specification | Optional |

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. At minimum 10 core templates present in resources/documents/templates/
2. All templates have proper markdown structure with placeholder variables
3. Templates are usable by agents without modification
4. SHA-256 checksums match in manifest

#### STORY 5: Resources Match Source

As a developer, I want bundled resources to match the source project exactly so that I get the latest agent capabilities.

**Requirement Details:**

1. The copy-resources.js build script MUST copy files from workspace root to resources/
2. The sync-from-source.ps1 script MUST sync from MCPOrchestration to FEC\_CR\_Builder
3. After running both scripts, bundled resources MUST be byte-identical to source

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. copy-resources.js copies all mapped paths correctly
2. No files are missed or extra files included
3. Skip rules exclude: node\_modules, \_\_pycache\_\_, out, dist, .git, settings, mcp.json
4. Running gen-checksums.js after copy produces valid manifest

#### STORY 6: Checksum Manifest for Modification Detection

As a developer, I want a checksum manifest so that the extension can detect if I’ve customized any files.

**Requirement Details:**

1. .sdlc-checksums.json MUST contain SHA-256 hash for every bundled file
2. Manifest includes version number and generation timestamp
3. Extension uses manifest to detect user modifications during “Update” command

**Acceptance Criteria:**

1. Manifest covers all files in resources/ (agents, steering, hooks, templates)
2. Each entry has: hash, version, injectedAt fields
3. Hashes are SHA-256 (64 hex characters)
4. Manifest version matches package.json version

